Imagine that you attend Quora Public High School. You start out as a freshman. You expect people to grab your head and push your face into the toilet, but that doesn’t happen to newbies. Feeling surprised about it, you keep your head low, knowing that it could happen at any moment. You gain friends out of nowhere. You answer questions. Sometimes they like it, and sometimes, a teacher will tell you that you have violated policy after policy without explaining why. You start and join clubs, called Spaces, and people start sharing their favourite stories, news articles and grandmother’s recipes. And then it happens: you’re popular now. Like other popular kids, you get bullied and harassed. You see, here in Quora Public High School, it’s the popular kids who get bullied, harassed and sent death threats, not the nerds. In a normal high school, it’s usually the other way around. But like a normal high school, if you complain to the teachers, you’re lucky if you get any justice. Instead, the unpopular kids will report you to the teachers, and BAM! You’re shunned. Edit-blocking in real life is shunning. People can like your stuff, but you can’t interact with them as you wander down the halls. Then another bombshell is dropped. What is it, you say? You’re banned. Expelled. No point of returning now, huh? In the meantime, people are laughing at your expense, saying that you deserved it. Others are petitioning for your return, but their pleas fall on deaf ears. Eventually, you stamp your feet in frustration and say, “Screw it! I’m going to Medium Private Academy!” And everyone will just shrug their shoulders and carry on with their lives. Yep, just another day at Quora Public High School.

The Internet is a rather strange place, and the world would be much stranger if things that happen on the internet were to happen in real life. Emojis.Kate just bought a new dress and she couldn’t wait to show it to her friends. As soon as she put it on, June materialised out of nowhere. “Whoa, Kate! You look gorgeous!” She cried. The next thing Kate knew, June’s eyeballs were bulging out of her sockets, except that they weren’t eyeballs at all. They’d turned into two red hearts, and were popping out of her head, quite literally. “Aw thanks so much!” Kate shrieked, pouting. A red heart floated in the air.  Likes and comments on social media.Kate was taking a walk in the park when suddenly, she tilted her head slightly towards her left and left behind an imprint of herself. June walked by the imprint a few seconds later and double-tapped Kate’s nose. A red heart appeared and disappeared instantly. More and more people came by and double-tapped her nose, some even talked to Kate’s imprint. “You go girl!” Zoe’s heart thumped out of her chest while she said that.  Google.Kate was doing an assignment but was stuck with a little piece of information. After several minutes of chewing the tip of her pen, she whispered to no-one in particular, “What are some ways to prevent communication barriers?” A woman revealed herself from the corner of Kate’s room. She wore a blue hat, a red t-shirt, yellow coloured pants. One of her socks was green while the other was red in colour. Kate had to admit, this woman had a pretty peculiar style. “Here are some ways to avoid barriers of communication…” Ms. Google says in a boring voice. Once Kate found what she was looking for, Ms. Google was nowhere to be seen.  Creeps.Kate was walking to school when a man she’d never met before blocked her way. “Hi sweetie wanna see my big peepee?” The man leered at Kate. Too late to do anything— the man had already flashed himself. Before he could say anything else, Kate gagged him and robot police took him away.  Quora.Kate was chilling on the terrace, minding her own business when a Kenyan guy who lived some four thousand miles away from her screamed through his mic. “What is the most embarrassing moment of your life?” Without a second thought, Kate brought her own mic closer to her mouth and replied, “One afternoon, I went to the local store to…” She finished talking, but her voice echoed all around the world for several years. Some people took off their headphones so that they could listen to her story, while some put on their headphones so that they didn’t have to listen to her story. A week passed by and Kate had already forgotten about it. Suddenly, a woman she didn’t recall talking to whispered in her ear, “Hahaha that was so funny! I remember how I…” A couple of months later, her voice stopped echoing. Dead silence. For Kate, at least. A voice shouted in her face. “Your answer violates Quora’s BNBR policy.”  I hope my answer does not violate Quora’s BNBR policy.

You keep walking. You see a big T-intersection where your only choice it to go left or right. There’s a guy at that intersection who grabs you by the collar and screams, “Choose a side!” On the left, you see some nightly news personalities, telling you the world is going to hell because the President of the US is tearing the world apart. You see a group of professors telling students that they need to “smash the patriarchy.” The students agree that capitalism is the scourge of the earth, and periodically use their iPhones to find their way to Facebook street to tell everyone how horrible capitalism is. As you walk down further on the left, you see a guy in a tie-die t-shirt who looks like he hasn’t bathed in weeks selling Che Guevara t-shirts for 20 bucks each. He got them made in Vietnam for 50 cents apiece. Keep walking down left street, and you’ll see a group of people dressed in black beating up elderly white people, gay Vietnamese journalists, and shutting down events. The press covers for them, saying that “a group of counter-protesters was caught up in a brawl.” Well, of course if you start the brawl you’re going to be caught up in it. Keep walking to the right, you’ll see a group of hunters posing next to dead animals sighing, “What a beautiful animal.” Seriously, if you think it’s beautiful take a picture or paint a painting. You don’t have to kill it. Keep walking to the right and there’s a group of guys in red hats and black and gold Fred Perry polo shirts just waiting for anybody in a black mask to walk by. Some of them are Hispanic, some are black. Many are white. They are dismayed that they get accused of being racist homophobes when one of their OG buddies is gay, married to a black man. However, they are proud of who they are, and many of them are former football players and they are very burly. These bearded guys love to drink beer, and they are not afraid of a fight. If you walk too far down this street, you start to see guys in white hoods. It’s hard to tell them apart from the guys in the black masks. The funny thing is, these guys don’t really belong here. They’ve been relocated here by the press. They started out where the guys in the black masks are now. Realizing you’re not in the real world anymore, you go back to main street. The people on the streets other than Left and Right street are completely unaware that Left and Right Street exist. There’s a run-down street called MySpace. There are old posters of Justin Bieber, but other than that it’s just a ghost town. You keep walking. There’s a street where 50 year old men are dressed up like 13 year old girls. It looks kinda fun for a while, but suddenly a naked cartoon runs into the street with a leather mask on, asking if you want to have an orgy with 5 men, a hermaphrodite, some short people, and a grandmother. You feel sick to your stomach. You walk on. There’s another street called YouTube. You stand there for a few hours. You have no idea how you started watching your favorite song ended up leading you to World Star Hip Hop street fights. But you saw some videos of Jordan Peterson destroying people and Ben Shapiro melting snowflakes. That reminds you, you need to get something for a friend’s birthday. You stop by Amazon street. While looking for a nice blouse or bouquet of flowers, you start to look down main street when suddenly the cartoon from Pron Street runs up again and asks you if you’d like to have an orgy with 5 obese people. You tell the naked cartoon to go away. Suddenly, another naked cartoon jumps up behind it. Suddenly there are 10 naked cartoons. You finally get rid of all the naked cartoons and run back down main street. You see the address of the pizza place you were looking for 6 hours ago. “OH, that’s what I was looking for.” You order your pizza and leave main street. 20 minutes later, you’re binging on hot pizza and Netflix.

In real life, would you give the keys of your home to a stranger? Leave your door open when you take a shower? Yet these seemingly overblown examples illustrate perfectly what we do with our data online. When talking about the hot topic of online privacy, a lot of companies offer various solutions out there from secured browsers to password manager, VPNs and more. But the truth is, it all comes down to digital habits more than tools. So the best approach to protecting one's online privacy is only to leave your data where you need it. Each time you go online, we leave behind hundreds of bits of information about us that are collected and stored. When these traces are put together not only can they give others tremendous insight into our lives, but they can also be used against us. So by reducing our digital footprint, we decrease the chance of compromising our data.
